C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Missile Warning / Missile Tracking - MEO Epoch 1                                                                              699.675     448.909      200.701

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
Description: This activity funds development of Medium Earth Orbit space vehicles, with two launches planned to deliver twelve
space vehicles by FY 2028, and ground efforts with operations necessary to deliver initial capability for the combined Low Earth
Orbit and Medium Earth Orbit architecture. Initial capability consists of regional tracking, mission management and control, and
coordinated regional warning and tracking access validated through on-orbit measurements. After performance validation is
complete, prototype sensors will feed data directly to operational warning and defense systems. Furthermore, the initial capability
will provide sensitivity to detect emerging threats, accurate tracking to contain maneuvering targets, and mission data delivery
within required latency timelines to close the kill-chain. Initial Warfighting Capability is now defined in the Overhead Persistent
Infrared Resilient Medium Earth Orbit/Low Earth Orbit Capability Development Document Annex as global missile tracking access
and will be provided in Epoch 2.

Data Fusion: Test, assess, and validate sensor performance on the ground and on-orbit to ensure track data is integrated by
program of record data and fusion operational programs such as FORGE (PE 1206440SF), Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead
Persistent Infrared Architecture, other classified partners and missions, research and development multi-intelligence fusion (PE
1206442SF), and intelligence characterization. Space Vehicle testing is on contract as of December 2022. Fusion software
studies underway with FORGE program as of March 2023. Additional early integration support and studies are planned with the
Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared Architecture to start in FY 2024. Additionally in FY 2024, sensor models will
begin to be built to support future modeling and simulation activities with the FORGE and Missile Defense program offices.

FY 2025 Plans:
Space: Begin Crucial Mission Payloads and Bus Assembly, Integration & Test activities. The Epoch 1 vendor intends to deliver at
least two flight payloads and satellite buses and start space vehicle level assembly, integration and testing by the end of FY 2025.
Complete launch vehicle integration studies and launch vehicle selection for both launches. Initiate Epoch 2 planning activities and
award contract(s) to execute space, ground, and integration. Epoch 2 will build out the architecture for global missile tracking with
up to four planes of additional capability.

FY 2025 marks the start of Epoch 2. Epoch 2 released a Request For Proposal in mid CY 2024 to support a mid FY 2025 contract
execution for space, ground, and integration. Epoch 2 will build out the architecture for global missile tracking with up to four
planes of additional capability. The USSF began early engagement with industry with Requests for Information in 2023 and has a
good understanding on industrial performance capabilities and cost. First vendor awarded 29 May 2025 for two planes of space
vehicles. Additional award planned by end of FY 2025.

Ground: Completion of space vehicle contractor software builds for both Command and Control and Mission Data Processing
and continues ground system integration and test into the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF; formerly the Tools,

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
Application's, and Processing Lab) in Boulder, Colorado. Continue to outfit the Medium Earth Orbit Space Operations Center at
the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF), including Ops floor build out allowing separate rooms for proprietary work for each
space vehicle vendors. Continue integration of space vehicle vendor ground hardware into the BGIF and establish interfacing
connectivity between the space vehicle vendors and Medium Earth Orbit Space Operations Center. The Operation and Integration
contractor, Parsons, will facilitate the integration of ground systems into the BGIF and will lead the Medium Earth Orbit Space
Operations Center Authority to Operate cyber security package to establish the Medium Earth Orbit Space Operations Center
enclave in preparation for initial testing and operations.

Delivery of six Hardware In the Loop test beds (developed by the Ground Entry Point Contractor, Northrop Grumman), to the
Epoch 1 space vehicle vendor each of the space vehicle vendors and begin supporting early space vehicle integration and
launch and early orbit testing on the testbeds. Deliver the 1st Ground Entry Point antenna to Schriever Space Force Base. The
contractor plans to deliver one antenna every month until all nine antennas have been delivered to their respective locations.
Begin Ground Entry Point Integration, test, validation, and verification in preparation for launch rehearsals and Launch and Early
On-Orbit Test campaign.

Data Fusion: Finalize sensor model builds and verification & validation campaigns to ensure the fidelity of the models are
adequate to be integrated into enterprise sensor test campaigns spanning the entire Overhead Persistent Infrared architecture.
In FY 2025, major simulation and ground test campaign planning will occur to ensure sensor models and live on-orbit data will be
ingested at the appropriate missile warning and missile defense test events occurring in FY 2026-2027.

The Ground Preliminary Design Review assessed the maturity of the design for both space vehicles contractors' ground solution
and Ground Entry Point antennas. The assessment included a detailed review of the Concept of Operations to in include the
interaction between the space vehicle system, subsystems, space vehicle ground, and external factories. The Preliminary Design
Review also included a review of the ground hardware design and Cyber Security Controls Traceability Matrix for the ground
segment to establish an allocated baseline to proceed to a detailed design in Critical Design Review.

Funds allow both space and ground efforts to rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness
necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies,
technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial and international opportunities.
FY 2026 Plans:
Space: Crucial deliveries of payloads and satellite buses from the remaining contractor for integration and assembly. The vendor
intends to deliver flight payloads and satellite buses for the first six satellites and begin space vehicle level assembly, integration
and testing. Millennium Space Systems will initiate assembling and testing space vehicle's 7-12 to complete two orbital planes of

