Remarks$$, $$Space: The Resilient Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit initiative began in FY 2019 as Next Gen Overhead Persistent Infrared "Block 1 Prototype”
under the Next Gen Overhead Persistent Infrared Space Modernization Initiative PE1206442SF. Six missile track custody prototype contracts were competitively
awarded under this effort which utilized a multi-phased contracting strategy to field an on-orbit Missile Track Custody Demonstration or the Missile Track Custody

 Demonstration space vehicle. Early efforts also included digital engineering risk reduction which serves as the foundation for current Resilient Missile Warning, Missile
 Tracking Medium Earth Orbit efforts.

 In FY 2021, following the completion of the Space Warfighting Analysis Center force design for the Missile Warning, Missile Tracking mission area, Missile Track
 Custody Demonstration efforts were formalized as Resilient Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 1. The May 2021 Epoch 1 contract awards
 were the result of a free, fair, and open competition where five vendors submitted proposals and two were selected to develop the first six vehicles for fielding no later
 than FY 2027 as Resilient Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 1. The Full Missile Warning/Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared
 Capability Development Document and Technical Requirements Document were included in the request for proposal. The Space Force will field Epoch 1 capability
 under current contracts that were competitively awarded for the first three vehicles from each contractor (Space Vehicles 1-6). In May 2022, the Space Force Program
 Executive Officer approved an acquisition strategy for all of Epoch 1 scope: Vehicles 1-6; additional vehicles to meet performance baseline (at least three); Command
 and Control software; Mission Data processing Software; Operations and Integration; and at least two Ground Entry Point sites (six total ground antennas) for command
 and telemetry.

 Epoch 1 Space: In January 2023, the Space Force Program Executive Officer approved the acquisition strategy for Epoch 1, nine space vehicles. That strategy has
 since been amended to include up to twelve Epoch 1 space vehicles as of September 2024. This was due to Raytheon being terminated as an Epoch 1 space vehicle
 vendor as a result of underperformance, and subsequent pursuit of an additional six space vehicles from Millennium Space Systems. The program delivered an
 integrated acquisition strategy for all of Epoch 1 to enter the acquisition pathway as a Middle Tier Acquisition and was formally deemed a Middle Tier Acquisition Rapid
 Prototyping acquisition program by the Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition and Sustainment in April 2024. The strategy included acceleration of
 additional spacecraft as part of the FY 2023 Congressional Add. The Epoch 1 requirements were derived from the Missile Warning and Missile Defense Overhead
 Persistent Infrared Enterprise Capability Development Document, validated by the Joint Requirement Oversight Council in May 2019. They are now derived from the
 Rapid Prototyping Requirement Document signed by the Chief Space Requirements Officer in January 2024. Epoch 1 serves as the first delivery of capability targeting
 regional warning and tracking coverage with launches in 2026 and 2027.

 Ground: The acquisition strategy for mission-unique ground portions of Epoch 1 were approved by the Program Executive Officer in May 2022. The Space Force will
 deliver Mission Data Processing and Command and Control software development under current contracts that were competitively awarded in FY 2021 under the Next
 Gen Overhead Persistent Infrared PE 1206442SF. A contract for the Ground Entry Points was awarded via a mission partner in December 2022, and an Operation and
 Integration contract award in May 2023 under the Missile Warning, Missile Tracking PE 1206447SF. Continuous updates to the Command and Control and Mission Data
 Processing software will be expected, and ground antenna contracts will continue execution led in collaboration with mission partners. The program office is leveraging
 a competitively awarded operations center and integration contract with General Services Administration for integrating and testing the ground system. The program
 developed an acquisition strategy for all of Epoch 1 scope: vehicles 1-6; additional vehicles to meet performance baseline (six additional space vehicles); Command
 and Control software; Mission Data Processing software; Operation and Integration, and at least six 13.5 meter ground antennas (three per site) for operating the space
 vehicles. Consideration is being given for additional smaller antennas to support Epoch 1 and future Epoch operations. Acquisition Strategy updates for changes in
 Ground development to support Epoch 2 were approved by the Service Acquisition Executive in Apr 2025, to include an addition of a backup Medium Earth Orbit Space
 Operations Center and additional GEP sites.

 Epoch 2 Space: Derives requirements from the Overhead Persistent Infrared Capability Development Document Medium Earth Orbit/Low Earth Orbit Annex, validated
 by the Joint Requirement Oversight Council in February 2024. This and all future Epochs are planned for competitive awards. The Epoch 2 acquisition strategy
 was approved by the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force for Space Acquisition in June 2024. This enabled contracts for the program to achieve Initial Warfighting
 Capabilities. They were granted permission to enter as a Middle Tier Acquisition Rapid Prototyping acquisition program by the Office of the Under Secretary of Defense
 for Acquisition and Sustainment and reaffirmed with the inclusion of Ground Management and Integration in April 2025.

