A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The United States Space Force Space Systems Command and Space Development Agency are collaborating to deliver Overhead Persistent Infrared capabilities, in
concert with Department of Defense and Intelligence Community partners, to support a proliferated space architecture that is resilient by design and capable of operating
through contested environments. Resilient Missile Warning/Missile Tracking - Medium Earth Orbit space and ground efforts pivot the Department of the Air Force's
legacy missile warning force design to a more resilient multi-orbit approach to counter advanced missiles, hypersonic glide vehicles, and fractional orbital bombardment
threats. Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit was originally anchored in Missile Warning and Missile Defense Capability Development Document
requirements validated by the Joint Requirements Oversight Council; there is now a Joint Requirement Oversight Council-approved Capability Development Document
Annex with very specific Medium Earth Orbit and Low Earth Orbit requirements. Constellation resiliency is foundational to the Department of the Air Force's Resilient
Missile Warning and Tracking force design, therefore, the Overhead Persistent Infrared Family of Systems, including Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth
Orbit, is designed to work cohesively to gain and maintain custody of a spectrum of missile threats.

 The Medium Earth Orbit program will deploy space assets in multiple Epochs to allow for incremental capability delivery and to ensure competition throughout the
 lifecycle of the program. Resilient Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit will bolster legacy Space Based Infrared Satellite and Next-Gen Overhead
 Persistent Infrared capabilities and will independently satisfy mission area Capability Development Document requirements for missile tracking by as early as FY
 2033. FY 2026 funding supports final build, test, and delivery of flight payloads and buses to support Epoch 1, space vehicle level assembly integration and test, and
 launch/early orbit operations. FY 2026 funding also includes ground activities previously captured in PE 1206448SF, Project 657124, that continue ground segment
 Mission Data Processing application development and integration, command and control software and facilities build and integration into the Medium Earth Orbit Space
 Operations Center, and ground entry point site construction to support on-orbit initialization in FY 2027. In order to preserve Epoch 1 schedule and avoid additional
 costs, the Program Executive Officer approved the transition of the space segment development to a single vendor as of September 2024.

 Space Systems Command, Space Development Agency, and the Missile Defense Agency will continue to use the Combined Program Office construct to develop and
 implement a system-of-systems integration strategy across for Missile Warning, Missile Tracking and Missile Defense constellations supporting Low Earth Orbit, Medium
 Earth Orbit, Geosynchronous Orbit and Polar Orbit regimes. Resilient Missile Warning, Missile Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 1 is now comprised of a single space
 vendor and multiple ground lines of effort to include the following:
 -Space vehicle development efforts are currently underway with Millennium Space Systems with the potential delivery of up to twelve space vehicles.
 -Delivery includes: design, build, hardware integration, testing, delivery, launch vehicle integration, space vehicle.



