C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
Description: This activity funds development of Medium Earth Orbit space vehicles, with two launches planned to deliver twelve
space vehicles by FY 2028, and ground efforts with operations necessary to deliver initial capability for the combined Low Earth
Orbit and Medium Earth Orbit architecture. Initial capability consists of regional tracking, mission management and control, and
coordinated regional warning and tracking access validated through on-orbit measurements. After performance validation is
complete, prototype sensors will feed data directly to operational warning and defense systems. Furthermore, the initial capability
will provide sensitivity to detect emerging threats, accurate tracking to contain maneuvering targets, and mission data delivery
within required latency timelines to close the kill-chain. Initial Warfighting Capability is now defined in the Overhead Persistent
Infrared Resilient Medium Earth Orbit/Low Earth Orbit Capability Development Document Annex as global missile tracking access
and will be provided in Epoch 2.

Data Fusion: Test, assess, and validate sensor performance on the ground and on-orbit to ensure track data is integrated by
program of record data and fusion operational programs such as FORGE (PE 1206440SF), Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead
Persistent Infrared Architecture, other classified partners and missions, research and development multi-intelligence fusion (PE
1206442SF), and intelligence characterization. Space Vehicle testing is on contract as of December 2022. Fusion software
studies underway with FORGE program as of March 2023. Additional early integration support and studies are planned with the
Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared Architecture to start in FY 2024. Additionally in FY 2024, sensor models will
begin to be built to support future modeling and simulation activities with the FORGE and Missile Defense program offices.

FY 2025 Plans:
Space: Begin Crucial Mission Payloads and Bus Assembly, Integration & Test activities. The Epoch 1 vendor intends to deliver at
least two flight payloads and satellite buses and start space vehicle level assembly, integration and testing by the end of FY 2025.
Complete launch vehicle integration studies and launch vehicle selection for both launches. Initiate Epoch 2 planning activities and
award contract(s) to execute space, ground, and integration. Epoch 2 will build out the architecture for global missile tracking with
up to four planes of additional capability.

FY 2025 marks the start of Epoch 2. Epoch 2 released a Request For Proposal in mid CY 2024 to support a mid FY 2025 contract
execution for space, ground, and integration. Epoch 2 will build out the architecture for global missile tracking with up to four
planes of additional capability. The USSF began early engagement with industry with Requests for Information in 2023 and has a
good understanding on industrial performance capabilities and cost. First vendor awarded 29 May 2025 for two planes of space
vehicles. Additional award planned by end of FY 2025.

Ground: Completion of space vehicle contractor software builds for both Command and Control and Mission Data Processing
and continues ground system integration and test into the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF; formerly the Tools,


