C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024       FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Enterprise Mission Integration and Analysis                                                                                          -             -        85.571
Description: Enterprise Mission Integration and Analysis assesses and validates the USSF's ability to close on mission threads
and kill chains to achieve space superiority and provide space support to the joint force. This effort executes end-to-end mission
thread analysis on 4+ operational scenarios needed for mission effects as identified in Combatant Commanders' Operational
Plans using System of Systems Engineering (SoSE) processes. This includes aligning cross-program interfaces, system-of-
systems tests, multiple program schedules, identifying gaps and driving integration requirements with the Chief Strategy and
Resourcing Officer (CSRO) for PEO acquisitions to meet warfighter needs. This synchronizes the USSF's existing, programmed,
and objective architectures to provide combat capabilities. It includes modeling and simulation tools, multi-level security data

RDT&E Management Support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                         FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
architecture, and subject matter expertise for analysis, communication, and collaboration across the space enterprise. This
includes rapid response to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space
domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk
reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities
to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.

This effort also supports the integration and modifications of USSF capabilities to realize the DAF Battle Network, enabling space
support to the joint fight, and increasing interoperability to achieve sensor-to-shooter effects. It includes the collection and analysis
of programmatic data to identify efficiencies and provide prioritization recommendations to USSF leadership. It also identifies and
advocates for critical technologies, industrial base capabilities, and active supply chain risk management. This effort provides
requirements and governance to maintain an integrated USSF Digital Ecosystem (interoperable and networked cloud, tools, data,
machines, and users) in partnership with USSF programs, which is essential to execute the above activities.

FY 2026 Plans:
Integrate space command and control (C2) capabilities across USSF PEO portfolios and mission partner organizations to close
kill chains and enable effective and resilient counterspace operations. Develop an end-to-end, system-of-systems test plan
to test the integration of 4+ weapon systems across the USSF needed to execute the Joint Space Operations Plan (JSOP).
The enterprise integration of these systems also require access to infrastructure, sensors, networks, cyber, and security which
requires touchpoints to 5+ program offices and respective mission partner organizations. Develop 12 critical and baselined
system-of-systems engineering documents to include operational capability to system-of-systems allocation matrix, enterprise
mission performance functionality allocations, DoD Architecture Framework (DoDAF) Systems Viewpoints to identify architecture
connections, and threat/target performance and characteristics associated with the operational scenarios. Complete analysis on
4+ operational scenarios at highly classified levels in support of the JSOP's C3BM scenarios associated with C5ISRT, Protect and
Defend, and Electronic Warfare/Joint Fires missions. The analysis will include cross-program interfaces, which spans validation
and verification of data link connections and message data formats needed for operational effectiveness, reliability/availability/
maintainability of systems across kill chains, and overarching interoperability. As discrepancies are identified, complete analysis
of cross-program interfaces will be done resulting in enterprise requirements that will be run through the SoSE processes for
governance and inserted into the enterprise technical baseline as necessary and in coordination with CSRO. Deliver capability
roadmaps to ensure multi-system readiness to find, fix, track, target, engage, and assess an engagement for all operational
scenarios. Develop in concert with partnered organizations integrated assessment plans resulting in participation of joint exercises
to deliver fully burdened combat ready capabilities to the USSF warfighter.

Expand analysis and integration into additional mission threads and provide USSF leadership recommendations on actions
needed to deliver an integrated space enterprise. Drive the use of next generation digital engineering capabilities a t the

RDT&E Management Support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
Combined Space Operations Center (CSpOC) to enable timely and effectively delivery space support to the Joint Force. Assess
threats to USSF terrestrial data transport infrastructure, identify high-risk locations and missions, and formulate resilience
measures that assure connectivity in competition and conflict. Coordinate with mission partners to integrate commercial antennas
into USSF tracking, telemetry, and control architecture and supporting resource scheduling systems. Assist program offices with
the integration of cyber-security and Defensive Cyber Operations capabilities into space weapon systems.

Provide the modeling, simulation and analysis tools and expertise needed for the above tasks. Transition prototype digital
