INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604201A$$, 2027, $$This PE provides funding to support modification and development activities necessary to support Aircraft Avionics modernization requirements to meet the evolving
Army Avionics priorities in support of the National Defense and National Military strategies.

 A portion of this program element, project C97, is directly aligned to the Assured Positioning, Navigation, and Timing (A-PNT) Army Modernization Priority. Tasks in
 this Program Element support research, development, and test efforts in the Engineering and Manufacturing Development phases of these systems. Alternate Position,
 Navigation, and Timing (ALT-PNT) capabilities, non-Global Positioning System (non-GPS), and/or complimentary Positioning, Navigation, and Timing (PNT) solutions
 will be studied and developed as standalone or blended navigation functions.

 A portion of this program element, project VU3, supports the development of hardware and the continuous integration and continuous development/delivery of software
 to meet both legacy and future aircraft platform avionics software and hardware requirements. Efforts include supporting Next Generation Command and Control
 (NGC2) requirements specified in the infrastructure annex of the NGC2 Initial Capabilities Document, while also addressing both the Improved Data Modem (IDM)
 obsolescence and necessary hardware and software enhancements to support emerging Army requirements and evolve Aviation platform capabilities in alignment
 with Army Senior Leader priorities. To meet the NGC2 requirements as specified in the infrastructure annex of the NGC2 Initial Capabilities Document, specifically, a
 software control plane so the compute environment is agnostic to the hardware and hardware that meets the Open-Source Container Initiative, this project supports the
 development of the General-Purpose Computing Platform (GPCP) to address both current hardware and software obsolescence issues of the IDM and the insertion of
 critical capabilities.

 A portion of this program element, project VU3, in parallel to the GPCP efforts supports the continuous integration and continuous development/delivery of the IDM/
 IDM Open Systems REMAN (OSR) Interoperability Software that requires upgrading to address emerging requirements, cyber security enhancements and additional
 capabilities to meet emerging Army requirements.

 A portion of this program element, project VU3, includes an FY26 Congressional Add for Bandwidth Enhanced - Common Data Link (BE-CDL) Mode 300 advanced
 networking and platform integration. This BE-CDL Mode 300 protected waveform initiative focuses on finalization of BE-CDL Mode 303 equipment for incorporation into
 Launched Effects (LE) and Uncrewed Aircraft System (UAS). This will be achieved by producing refined networked waveform firmware and software, sufficient airborne
 kits for networked LE usage flight testing, performing full network sized flight test, incorporate fixes based on National Security Agency (NSA) testing, and continued
 development of C5ISR Modular Open Suite of Standards (CMOSS) Mounted Form Factor (CMFF) based BE-CDL Mode 303 communications solutions for rotary wing
aircraft. These, and other key items will enable adoption of this critically necessary technology for use in contested electronic warfare areas in anti-access area denial
 (A2AD) battlespace.$$, $$Supports the development of hardware and the continuous integration and continuous development/delivery of software to meet both legacy and future aircraft platform
avionics software and hardware requirements.

 To meet the Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) requirements as specified in the infrastructure annex of the NGC2 Initial Capabilities Document,
 specifically, a software control plane so the compute environment is agnostic to the hardware and hardware that meets the Open-Source Container Initiative, a
 General-Purpose Computing Platform (GPCP) will be developed. The Improved Data Modem REMAN (IDM OSR), effort cannot incorporate the NGC2 requirements
 in time to mitigate obsolescence issues or meet the requirement to remove and replace (no modification to the aircraft) the IDM 401 with the IDM OSR. Therefore,
 the development program for the GPCP is critical to address both IDM obsolescence and necessary hardware and software enhancements to support emerging
 Army requirements and evolve Aviation platform capabilities in alignment with Army Senior Leader priorities. The GPCP development program will include the design,
 qualification, and demonstration of a GPCP that meets critical Army capability use-cases that will provide Army Aviation platforms the ability to rapidly apply technology
 upgrades utilizing a Modular Open Systems Approach (MOSA) with a nonproprietary Open Systems Architecture (OSA) to keep pace with evolving threats within
 multiple battlefield domains. The GPCP will enable the hosting of applications to communicate, navigate, sense, and deploy weapon systems across the Joint Force in
 support of Army Transformation in Contact and future aviation operations. It supports the future Common Digital Backbone for the enduring and future Army Aviation
 fleets with the ability to host flight critical capabilities and Next Generation Command and Control data forms. The Vendor(s) will be required to deliver three functional
 prototypes at end of contract.

 In parallel to the GPCP efforts, the IDM OSR Interoperability Software will require upgrading to meet NGC2 data requirements and the integration of other key
 requirements such as Mounted Mission Command-Transport that will provide improved situational awareness and command-and-control message delivery as well
 as satellite communication capabilities by increasing resiliency and integrating additional communications pathways. These efforts include the continuous integration
 and continuous development/delivery (CI/CD) of the IDM/IDM Open Systems REMAN (OSR) Interoperability Software that requires upgrading to address emerging
 requirements, cyber security enhancements and the integration of key capabilities to meet Army requirements. The IDM OSR will replace the IDM 401 and serve as
 the computing platform until replaced by the GPCP, these efforts will ensure the Software is maintained and updated to meet new requirements key to continued air-to-
 ground and air-to-air operations.

 An FY26 Congressional Add was received for Bandwidth Enhanced - Common Data Link (BE-CDL) Mode 300 advanced networking and platform integration. This BE-
 CDL Mode 300 protected waveform initiative focuses on finalization of BE-CDL Mode 303 equipment for incorporation into Launched Effects (LE) and Uncrewed Aircraft
 System (UAS). This will be achieved by producing refined networked waveform firmware and software, sufficient airborne kits for networked LE usage flight testing,
 performing full network sized flight test, incorporate fixes based on National Security Agency (NSA) testing, and continued development of C5ISR Modular Open Suite of

 adoption of this critically necessary technology for use in contested electronic warfare areas in anti-access area denial (A2AD) battlespace.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025        FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: Improved Data Modem Open Systems Reman and General-Purpose Computing Platform (GPCP)                                            1.736          2.696       30.658
Description: The IDM OSR provides air-to-air and air-to-ground communications, both voice and data. The IDM OSR supporting
software, Interoperability Software Application (ISA), is being rearchitected for ease of adding additional functionality and
restructured to meet Future Airborne Capability Environment (FACE). The FACE Technical Standard is an open real-time
standard for making safety-critical computing operations more robust, interoperable, portable and secure. The standard enables
software developers to create and deploy a wide catalog of applications for use across the entire spectrum of real-time systems
through a common operating environment. These efforts further promote application interoperability and portability with enhanced
requirements for exchanging data among FACE components. The intent is to develop software that is more agile and reactive to
meet emerging requirements from both a standard and user-requirements perspective.

FY 2026 Plans:
Funds engineering services and airworthiness support for the IDM Open System REMAN.
FY 2027 Plans:
Funds IDM OSR Software Development and Integration Requirements.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 funding increase will be used to re-architect the IDM 401's Interoperability Software Application (ISA) utilizing the
continuous improvement/continuous deployment model, to include software testing, platform software/hardware integration, and
cyber security activities to support the creation of a software environment. The goal is to create an agile and modular software
operating environment that aligns with Future Airborne Capability Environment (FACE) and Modular Open Systems Approach
(MOSA) standards. This new system will allow for the rapid integration of new capabilities for Army aircraft, reduce costs and
vendor dependency, and enable the swift adoption of new technologies to counter evolving threats through a common operating
environment.
